---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>Procedural <code>await</code> chains are fine if you’re casually scripting a weekend project. But if you’re orchestrating an autonomous mathematical research lab, they’re a liability.</p>

<p>The original orchestration layer of Perqed was a monolithic, 463-line class filled with deeply nested <code>while</code> loops, brittle prompt injection, and ad-hoc error recovery. Sure, it got the job done, but it was tedious to maintain and essentially impossible to formally verify. When you're running neuro-symbolic Monte Carlo Tree Search against the Lean 4 kernel, building your orchestration layer on top of spaghetti code shouldn't be the bottleneck.</p>

<h2>The Obvious Solution: Reactive XState v5</h2>

<p>The fix was trivial, really: we just ripped out the procedural logic entirely and replaced it with a strictly typed, 10-state reactive state machine using <strong>XState v5</strong>.</p>

<p>Instead of a tangled web of asynchronous calls, the entire research lifecycle—from literature ideation to empirical sandboxing, SMT-LIB2 resolution, and formal verification—is now a clean, mathematical Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG).</p>

<h2>Actor-Model Purity</h2>

<p>We neatly wrapped the existing agents into 8 isolated <code>fromPromise</code> actors. The actors hold zero mutable state. They simply receive structured inputs and return typed outputs, letting the state machine handle the transition logic completely detached from the agents themselves.</p>

<p>Need to handle a hallucinated Lean 4 syntax tree? Expected. The <code>Validation</code> actor throws, the machine catches it, increments a strongly-typed <code>ideaRetries</code> counter, and gracefully cycles back to the <code>Ideation</code> node. No sweat.</p>

<p>If the Empirical Sandbox detects a structural plateau instead of a clean counter-example, the state machine effortlessly routes the context to the <code>SMT_Resolution</code> node to query Z3 before it even thinks about escalating back to Lean. It's fully deterministic by design.</p>

<h2>TDD Topology Verification</h2>

<p>Because the orchestration is now represented as pure state transitions, testing it was almost too easy. We spun up an 8-test suite using Bun and XState's <code>.provide()</code> API to inject mocked actors without spinning up expensive LLMs.</p>

<p>We completely verified the 10-state topology—mapping the happy paths, falsification forks, plateaus, and terminal failure states—in exactly 95 milliseconds with zero API calls. 8 topology bounds checked. 8 tests green.</p>

<p>The Mathematician is no longer just in the box. Now it’s running on a mathematically sound, self-healing track.</p>
`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Reactive Math: Migrating Perqed to XState v5 — Perqed" activeNav="blog">

  <article class="article">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose">
        <header class="article-header">
          <div class="article-meta">
            <time>March 31, 2026</time>
            <span class="sep">·</span>
            <span>3 min read</span>
          </div>
          <h1>Reactive Math: Migrating Perqed's Core to XState v5</h1>
        </header>

        <div set:html={blogContent} />
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

</BaseLayout>

